byline.original: By Nancy Wartik and Daniel E. Slotnik

docs.abstract: Apple is taking small steps toward India. But the production of its latest phone, introduced on Wednesday, shows how difficult it will be to make big changes.
docs.snippet: Apple is taking small steps toward India. But the production of its latest phone, introduced on Wednesday, shows how difficult it will be to make big changes.
docs.lead_paragraph: This fall, Apple will make some of its flagship iPhones outside China for the first time, a small but significant change for a company that has built one of the most sophisticated supply chains in the world with the help of the Chinese authorities. But the development of the iPhone 14, which was unveiled on Wednesday, shows how complicated it will be for Apple to truly untangle itself from China.

headline.main: How China Has Added to Its Influence Over the iPhone
headline.print_headline: China’s Tangled Role in iPhone Keeps Apple From Straying Far

docs.abstract: Apple has long supported privacy and shunned those intrusive ads. What happens when it sells more ads, too?
docs.snippet: Apple has long supported privacy and shunned those intrusive ads. What happens when it sells more ads, too?
docs.lead_paragraph: For years, Apple has been a loud critic of online advertising that relies on hogging as much information about us as possible. Now, the company wants to become a bigger seller of online ads, and says it can do so in a less creepy way.

headline.main: Apple, the Ad Critic, Now Embraces Ads

docs.abstract: Worried about geopolitical tensions and stung by pandemic shutdowns, Google, Apple and others are moving some work to nearby countries.
docs.snippet: Worried about geopolitical tensions and stung by pandemic shutdowns, Google, Apple and others are moving some work to nearby countries.
docs.lead_paragraph: In the coming weeks, Apple and Google will unveil their latest generation of smartphones, jockeying to distinguish the new devices from previous models. But one of the most significant changes will go largely unnoticed by consumers: Some of these phones will not be made in China.

headline.main: Tech Companies Slowly Shift Production Away From China
headline.print_headline: Tech Makers Weaning Themselves From China

docs.abstract: Jobs growth is slowing but still strong. Bed Bath & Beyond gets a reprieve. A former Uber executive goes to trial.
docs.snippet: Jobs growth is slowing but still strong. Bed Bath & Beyond gets a reprieve. A former Uber executive goes to trial.
docs.lead_paragraph: After a surprising jobs report in July, which showed employers adding jobs at a blistering pace, August’s numbers fell more in line with expectations. The economy gained 315,000 jobs last month, well within range of the roughly 300,000 that forecasters had projected. That was a significant deceleration for the labor market — and is just what the Federal Reserve was looking for. Policymakers at the central bank have been trying to slow job growth as part of their campaign to rein in inflation and cool the economy. The Fed is likely to see this latest jobs report as a sign that its policies are working, but it well knows that its work isn’t over. The August jobs numbers still reflect a strong pace of growth, and Jerome H. Powell, the Fed chair, has indicated that there is little that would sway the central bank from its path of raising rates, including at its Sept. 20-21 meeting.

headline.main: The Week in Business: Job Growth Is Solid but Slowing
